ts of mega-events. Thus he suggests that contemporary mega-events, both in their achievements and their vulnerabilities, reflect, in the media sphere, the rise of the internet; in the urban sphere, de-industrialisation and the growing ecological crisis; and in the global sphere, the relative decline of the West and the rise of China and other ‘emerging’ countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEntertainment eventsxSocial aspects. 0aOlympicsxSocial aspects. 0aSocial change. 0aSpecial eventsxSocial aspects. 0aSports tournamentsxSocial aspects. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Olympics & Paralympics.2bisacsh  aExpos.  aOlympics.  aPeople's Republic of China.  adigital revolution.  aecological crisis.  ageopolitical relations.  aglobal ecological crisis.  aglobalisation.  agreen impacts.  amega-events.  amodernisation processes.  aperformative spectacles.  aspace-making impacts.  aurbanisation.1 aRoche, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611709040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526117090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526117090/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles